---
<figure class="orbit-instrument" aria-labelledby="orbit-instrument-title">
  <div class="instrument-toolbar">
    <p class="eyebrow">Spectral orbit plate</p>
    <span>Projection layer, not physical scale</span>
  </div>
  <div class="orbit-stage" role="img" aria-label="Spectral orbit trace plate of the Sun, Mercury, Venus, Earth, Moon, Mars, Phobos, and Deimos">
    <span class="field-contour contour-a"></span>
    <span class="field-contour contour-b"></span>
    <span class="field-contour contour-c"></span>
    <span class="orbit-ring ring-mercury"></span>
    <span class="orbit-ring ring-venus"></span>
    <span class="orbit-ring ring-earth"></span>
    <span class="orbit-ring ring-mars"></span>
    <span class="gravity-vector vector-earth"></span>
    <span class="gravity-vector vector-mars"></span>
    <span class="body-dot sun" data-label="Sun"></span>
    <span class="body-dot mercury" data-label="Mercury"></span>
    <span class="body-dot venus" data-label="Venus"></span>
    <span class="body-dot earth" data-label="Earth"></span>
    <span class="body-dot moon" data-label="Moon"></span>
    <span class="body-dot mars" data-label="Mars"></span>
    <span class="body-dot phobos" data-label="Phobos"></span>
    <span class="body-dot deimos" data-label="Deimos"></span>
    <div class="instrument-readout">
      <h2 id="orbit-instrument-title">Trace plate for eight simulated bodies</h2>
      <p>Real state lives in meters. This plate is an index of current catalog coverage and renderer responsibilities.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <figcaption>
    A measurement diagram, not a planet poster: labels, visible orbits, and projection cues make the physics/rendering boundary inspectable.
  </figcaption>
</figure>
